note.p: Black (0030099) reads the following here: "<aois an tighearna an tan> teasda Domhnall Ballac mac Eoin mhoir 1476."
This date is significantly eroded compared to the surrounding text, possibly as a result of an attempt to rub it out.
"Aois 1645" looks like it has been written in Niall MacMhuirich's hand, using a different pen and ink (black instead of brown).

Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". While one might expect Partholon to be attempting to disrupt his brother's succession in his own favour, the fact that the passage goes on to state that his brother assumed the kingship with no apparent conflict with Parthalon suggests that Parthalon was acting on his brother's behalf.

note.p: This is not the normal sobriquet for Óengus Ollam. Also, there are two unexplained and difficult-to-read characters ("re"?) written in superscript above "gail-".
The fir chula could be a population group of they could be the "men of protection", that is, some sort of bodyguard. The fact that tribute was imposed on them (see below) suggests the former.

Something seems to have been inserted but between "ro haghnacht" and "agus", although erosion means it cannot now be read. It would make sense for "ann" ("he was buried there") or suchlike to have been added here.
